```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class X
{
    public double p { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }

    // Constructor
    public X(double probability, string name)
    {
        p = probability;
        Name = name;
    }
}

public class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Create a list of X objects
        List<X> xList = new List<X>();
        xList.Add(new X(0.8, "Item1"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.4, "Item2"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.6, "Item3"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.9, "Item4"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.3, "Item5"));

        // Sort the list based on random number related to p
        xList.Sort((x1, x2) => -1 * x1.p.CompareTo(x2.p) + new Random().Next(-1, 2));

        // Print the sorted list
        foreach (var item in xList)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(item.Name + " - Probability: " + item.p);
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, we have a class `X` with properties `p` (probability) and `Name`. We create a List<X> and add some objects to it. The list is then sorted using the `Sort` method, where we pass a custom comparer that first compares the `p` values (-1 * x1.p.CompareTo(x2.p)) and then adds a random number (new Random().Next(-1, 2)) to determine the order when `p` values are the same.

Finally, we iterate over the sorted list and print the items with their names and probabilities.

Please note that the Random object is created within the sorting method, so each time you run the code, the list will be sorted differently due to the random component in the comparison.

If you want to randomly choose an item from a sorted list based on the probabilities (p) of each item, you can use a random selection approach called weighted random selection. Here's an example of how you can achieve that in C#:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class X
{
    public double p { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }

    public X(double probability, string name)
    {
        p = probability;
        Name = name;
    }
}

public class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        List<X> xList = new List<X>();
        xList.Add(new X(0.8, "Item1"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.4, "Item2"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.6, "Item3"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.9, "Item4"));
        xList.Add(new X(0.3, "Item5"));

        // Sort the list based on p in descending order
        xList.Sort((x1, x2) => -1 * x1.p.CompareTo(x2.p));

        // Choose an item randomly based on probabilities
        X chosenItem = ChooseRandomlyBasedOnProbability(xList);

        Console.WriteLine("Chosen Item: " + chosenItem.Name);
    }

    static X ChooseRandomlyBasedOnProbability(List<X> itemList)
    {
        // Calculate the sum of probabilities
        double totalProbability = 0;
        foreach (var item in itemList)
        {
            totalProbability += item.p;
        }

        // Generate a random number between 0 and the total probability
        double randomNumber = new Random().NextDouble() * totalProbability;

        // Iterate through the items and find the chosen item
        double cumulativeProbability = 0;
        foreach (var item in itemList)
        {
            cumulativeProbability += item.p;
            if (randomNumber <= cumulativeProbability)
            {
                return item;
            }
        }

        // If no item is chosen within the loop, return the last item
        return itemList[itemList.Count - 1];
    }
}
```

In this modified code, after sorting the list based on the `p` values in descending order, we define a method called `ChooseRandomlyBasedOnProbability` to perform the random selection. It takes the sorted list as a parameter.

Inside the method, we firstly calculate the total probability by summing up all the `p` values. Then, we generate a random number between 0 and the total probability. Next, we iterate over the items and find the chosen item by comparing the cumulative probability. The probability of choosing an item is weighted based on its `p` value.

After choosing an item using the `ChooseRandomlyBasedOnProbability` method, we can work with that selected item as needed.

Keep in mind that the chosen item will be random but weighted according to its probability. Items with higher `p` values will be more likely to be selected.

If you want to ensure that the outcomes of multiple calls to the `ChooseRandomlyBasedOnProbability` method are different each time, you can initialize the `Random` object outside of the method and pass it as a parameter. This ensures that the same instance of the `Random` object is used for each call, preventing the sequence from being reseeded and producing the same random number.

